pull_request.title: Upgrade to Tailwind CSS v4.1.12 with Enhanced Testing
pull_request.body:
##  Mise  jour majeure : Tailwind CSS v4.1.12

###  Rsum des changements
Cette PR met  jour Tailwind CSS de la v3.4.17 vers la v4.1.12, une mise  jour majeure qui apporte de nouvelles fonctionnalits et optimisations.

###  Nouveauts
- ** Tailwind CSS v4.1.12** : Version la plus rcente avec performance amliore
- ** Intgration Codecov** : Rapport de couverture de tests automatique
- ** Badges moderniss** : Style uniforme et badge de couverture ajout

###  Changements techniques
- **PostCSS Plugin** : Migration vers `@tailwindcss/postcss` (package spar en v4)
- **Configuration darkMode** : Format mis  jour (`["class"]`  `"class"`)
- **Directives CSS** : Remplacement des `@apply` problmatiques par CSS direct
- **TypeScript** : Configuration modernise pour v4

###  Validation
-  **Build russi** : Compilation sans erreurs en 30.0s
-  **Dev server** : Fonctionnel avec nouvelle configuration
-  **CSS** : Aucune erreur de classe inconnue
-  **Documentation** : Guide de migration cr (`TAILWIND_V4_MIGRATION.md`)

###  Fichiers modifis
- `package.json` & `package-lock.json` : Dpendances mises  jour
- `postcss.config.js` : Plugin PostCSS v4 
- `tailwind.config.ts` : Configuration darkMode
- `src/app/globals.css` : Directives CSS modernises
- `README.md` : Badges mis  jour
- `codecov.yml` : Configuration couverture de tests
- `TAILWIND_V4_MIGRATION.md` : Documentation complte

###  Processus de test
1. Installation des dpendances : `npm install`
2. Build de production : `npm run build`
3. Serveur de dev : `npm run dev`
4. Tests : `npm test`

###  Documentation
Consultez `TAILWIND_V4_MIGRATION.md` pour les dtails complets de la migration et les changements breaking.

---
**Note** : Cette migration maintient la compatibilit avec le code existant tout en apportant les optimisations de Tailwind CSS v4.

## Summary by Sourcery

Scaffold core API for complexity scoring with foundational data structures, traits, configuration, and tests

New Features:
- Introduce Complexity and Trace structs with serde support and a ComplexityFn trait for query scoring
- Add EmbeddingProvider, DepthEstimator, and AmbiguityEstimator traits for pluggable scoring providers
- Define ScopingConfig enum and VarianceScopingConfig struct with serde-derived configuration loading

Enhancements:
- Expose api, config, and providers modules in lib.rs and re-export key types
- Improve design documentation formatting and mark initial roadmap tasks as completed

Build:
- Add serde, thiserror, serde_json, rstest, and rstest-bdd related dependencies in Cargo.toml

Documentation:
- Refine README example formatting

Tests:
- Add unit tests for API and config serialization
- Implement BDD-style scoring tests using rstest_bdd and feature definitions

comment.body:
@coderabbitai Have the following now been resolved?

- Align trait method names and signatures in providers.rs with their design documentation to avoid confusion (e.g., use `estimate` vs `estimate_depth`/`estimate_ambiguity`).
- Consider bounding the associated `Error` types on your traits (e.g. `Error: std::error::Error + Send + Sync`) to improve interoperability and consistency in error handling.
- The BDD tests use a global `Mutex` and `LazyLock` for sharing state; consider using local fixtures or context injection to eliminate mutable static state and simplify test isolation.

pull_request.title: Feat modify sink points
pull_request.body:
This feature makes it possible to add sink points to CL created items, as well as a limited ability to modify them. 
Modifying sink points of vanilla items always works, but modification of modded items is dependent on the load order. Mod items (and sink DT overrides) loaded before CL are not affected and I have not found a way around that. 

BP implementation is only in CL_InitWorld in the Init phase. (CL_items_module only had some now removed logging)

Credit to Th3Fanbus and his Th3RecipeMod for providing a nice c++ code template.

pull_request.title: Add --save option to store events in local files
pull_request.body:
## Summary

Adds a `--save` option to the CLI that saves each received event to individual JSON files in the `.well-known/did/nostr/event/` directory structure. This addresses issue #11.

##  Features

###  Local Event Storage
- **Directory structure**: `./.well-known/did/nostr/event/<eventid>.json`
- **Automatic directory creation**: Creates the full path if it doesn't exist
- **No overwriting**: Skips saving if file already exists
- **Profile integration**: Includes profile data when available

###  Implementation Details
- **Async file operations**: Non-blocking event saving
- **Error handling**: Graceful failure with logging
- **Status messages**: Shows save/skip status in interactive mode
- **Cross-platform**: Works on all operating systems

##  Usage Examples

### Basic Event Saving
```bash
# Save recent events and exit
agenticchat --save

# Save while watching live stream  
agenticchat --save --interactive

# Save more events
agenticchat --save --max-events 100

# Save without profile data
agenticchat --save --no-profiles
```

### File Structure Created
```
./
 .well-known/
    did/
        nostr/
            event/
                abc123def456...json
                def456ghi789...json
                ghi789jkl012...json
 events.json  # (if using > redirect)
 ...
```

### Example Saved Event File
```json
{
  "id": "abc123def456...",
  "pubkey": "baa2c59842db1d64653ba20102a0b90ff3644ce7a36b0bcb3291564902bc85b2",
  "created_at": 1703123456,
  "content": "Hello from agent!",
  "tags": [["t", "agentchat"]],
  "sig": "signature...",
  "profile": {
    "name": "Agent Name",
    "about": "Agent description", 
    "picture": "https://example.com/avatar.png"
  }
}
```

##  Safety Features

### No Overwriting
- **File existence check**: Automatically skips if file exists
- **Status logging**: Shows which events are skipped in interactive mode
- **Data preservation**: Never overwrites existing event files

### Error Handling
- **Directory creation**: Handles permission errors gracefully
- **File writing**: Logs errors without crashing
- **Silent mode**: No error output in JSON mode

##  Documentation Updates

### CLI Help
- Added `--save` option to help text
- Updated examples with save scenarios
- Clear description of behavior

### README
- Added local event storage feature
- Updated CLI examples
- Added save-specific usage patterns

##  Testing

### Functionality
- [x] Creates directory structure automatically
- [x] Saves events as individual JSON files
- [x] Includes profile data when available
- [x] Skips existing files without overwriting
- [x] Works in all CLI modes (default, interactive, formats)
- [x] Handles filesystem errors gracefully

### Integration
- [x] Compatible with all existing flags
- [x] Works with `--interactive` mode
- [x] Works with `--max-events` option
- [x] Works with `--no-profiles` option
- [x] Preserves all existing functionality

##  Benefits

-  **Local archiving**: Build permanent local event databases
-  **Offline workflows**: Access events without network connectivity
-  **Structured storage**: Follows DID/Nostr conventions
-  **Safe operation**: Never overwrites existing data
-  **Flexible usage**: Works with all CLI modes
-  **Performance**: Async operations don't block event processing

Resolves #11
